# Secrets and Environment Variables

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

These rules have no exceptions. There is no scenario — not a development
environment, not a "temporary" value, not a value that "isn't really
sensitive" — that permits hardcoding a secret in source code.

Prohibited judgement calls:
- "It's just a dev key, it's fine to hardcode." — No. Read it from an environment variable.
- "I'll commit the `.env` file so it's easier for others." — No. `.env` is in `.gitignore` and must stay there.
- "The `detect-secrets` flag is a false positive, I'll skip the audit." — No. Audit every flag before adding it to the baseline, and document the reason.
- "I'll log this token at debug level — it's only visible in dev." — No. Never log secrets at any level.
- "I'll read `.env` to verify the user set it up correctly." — No. Never read `.env` under any circumstances.
- "I'll use a glob pattern like `.env*` to find `.env.example`." — No. Use the exact filename `.env.example` only. A glob that matches `.env` is prohibited.
- "I need to check what credentials are configured." — No. Ask the user. Never read `.env`.

## ABSOLUTE PROHIBITION: Never read .env

Reading `.env` pulls live credentials into the agent context. This is a
critical security violation that can expose database passwords, API keys,
SMTP credentials, and connection strings. There is no task — not
verification, not debugging, not reconnaissance — that justifies it.

The only permitted source of information about environment variable
configuration is `.env.example`. Read that file only when the user has
explicitly pointed you to it or asked you to check it.

If you are about to call any file-reading tool on a path that is or
might be `.env`, stop. Do not proceed. Ask the user instead.

If you are about to use a glob pattern that could match `.env` (e.g.
`.env*`, `**/.env*`), stop. Use the exact filename `.env.example` instead.

If you are about to write a literal value that could be a credential,
stop. Put it in an environment variable instead.

---

No credentials, API keys, tokens, passwords, or connection strings may appear in source code or committed files.

## Rules

- All sensitive values must be read from environment variables at runtime, never hardcoded.
- `.env` files are never committed to source control — they are in `.gitignore`.
- `secretlint` scans for secrets in all source files. Run as part of `./make.ps1 lint`.
  Config lives in `.secretlintrc.json`. Add new rules as needed when integrating
  new service types.
- If `secretlint` flags a false positive, add an inline `// secretlint-disable`
  comment on that line. Document the reason in a code comment on the same line.
  Never disable an entire file without explicit user approval.
- Never log secrets, tokens, or passwords — not even at `debug` level.
- Connection strings (database URL, Redis URL) are read from environment variables only.
- Secret rotation (e.g. `SECRET_KEY`) invalidates all active sessions — coordinate before rotating in production.

## What counts as a secret

- Flask `SECRET_KEY`
- Database credentials / connection strings
- API keys (LegiScan, external services)
- Redis passwords
- Any value that would cause a security incident if leaked

## See also

`detect-secrets` is run as part of the full linter suite. See `linter-must-pass.mdc`.
